<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-559-183  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 559 183.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Robotics Today  Fall 1990 v3 n3 p1(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Robots take off in aircraft paint stripping. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sturdivant, Vernon; Weniger, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Aircraft surface inspection, repair or other maintenanceoperations often necessitate removal of the paint on theaircraft's surface.andP;  The process does not lend itself to expedientor environmentally safe execution.andP;  The US Air Force has usedmanual chemical stripping, plastic media blasting (PMB) orsanding.andP;  PMB is considered safe and feasible but manual PMB isincredibly tedious and few are willing to do it.andP;  SouthwestResearch Institute (SWRI) is building a robotic system that willfree human operators from the noisy, monotonous work.andP;  The robotsremove paint automatically from fighter aircraft without damagingthe surface.andP;  The mechanism includes two robots (one for each sideof the airplane), two controllers, a cell control computer, paintsensors and blasting equipment.andP;  Sensors monitor the level ofplastic blasting medium in a hopper, delivering more to the systemwhen levels drop to a given point.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     RobotsAircraftMaintenanceProduct DevelopmentPaintingUnited States. Air ForceSouthwest Research Institute.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphchartdiagram.andO;Caption:   Paint stripping simulation, test results. (graph)Process control loop. (chart)Paint stripping robot. (diagram)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>